      commentary: `Three qualities are named as the conditions for receiving knowledge: faith (śraddhā), devotion to the pursuit (tat-paraḥ), and mastery of the senses. These are not prerequisites that you either have or don't — they are qualities you cultivate. The order is also significant: faith comes first.\n\nFaith here does not mean blind belief. Śraddhā is closer to earnestness — a genuine orientation toward truth that is willing to receive what comes. The person who approaches wisdom defensively, already knowing what they think, cannot receive anything new. Faith is the openness that makes learning possible.\n\nWhat you have faith in, you become — in secret, gradually, and then completely. This is the Gita's understanding of identity formation: not what you profess but what you genuinely orient toward. And the promise at the end of the verse is specific and unconditional: knowledge attained in this way leads to supreme peace — quickly. Not eventually. Quickly.`,
