      commentary: `Following the luminous promise of verse 39 — that the faithful seeker quickly attains supreme peace — this verse shows the mirror image. Three types of person are named, and they are not entirely separate: the ignorant (ajña), the faithless (aśraddadhāna), and the doubting self (saṁśayātmā). Each is a deeper form of the same problem.\n\nIgnorance can be corrected through inquiry. Faithlessness is more serious — it is the refusal to be open, the closure of the receiving channel. But saṁśaya — doubt that has become the dominant self-identification — is the most binding of all. Not ordinary doubt, which is healthy and questioning, but the kind of paralysing, self-consuming doubt that cannot commit to anything because it secretly believes nothing is worth committing to.\n\nThe consequence described is stark: not this world, not the next world, not happiness. This does not mean eternal damnation. It means that the doubting self cannot be present to any world it inhabits. It is always somewhere between possibilities, never arriving. Neither here nor there, never able to taste the fullness of a single moment. That absence of arrival is itself the loss described.`
