      commentary: `The chapter ends where it must: not in theory, but in action. The sword of knowledge is not a metaphor for intellectual argument. It is the quality of direct, clear seeing that cuts through the fog of doubt and self-deception. And the doubt being described — saṁśaya — is not mere intellectual uncertainty. It is the paralysis that settles in the heart when you cannot decide, cannot commit, cannot trust yourself enough to move.\n\nDoubt has a birthplace: ajñāna — ignorance. Not stupidity, but the particular confusion that comes from not knowing what you truly are. When you know yourself — really know, not just conceptually — the doubt dissolves. Not all at once. But systematically, as clarity replaces confusion.\n\nThe brutal truth about why you are not moving forward is often right here: the doubt that lives in the heart, fed by ignorance of your own nature, is making every decision tentative, every commitment provisional, every beginning incomplete. Cut it. Not with force but with knowledge. Know yourself. Then arise.`,
